This course focused on ideas formed in artistic expression proven to be scientifically sound. Literary works, paintings, musical scores and scientific journal articles are motivations for student writing. &#8232;&#8232;
Students found the course subject and assigned readings “very interesting,” and called the skills that they learned “valuable”. However, some students complained they “did not feel intellectually stimulated”. &#8232;&#8232;
Students had trouble connecting with Professor Charbonnier's teaching methodology, and felt her instructions were “very confusing and unhelpful.” Students also complained that Professor Charbonnier's grading was “wild” and “unnecessarily hard”. &#8232;&#8232;
The workload for this course was “demanding,” and a great deal more than what is expected in other writing seminars. Students were unsure of what to expect in terms of grades and feedback on portfolios, and felt “drained” by the amount of work required.

